10770540@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Creation==@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10770550@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==Operation==@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10770560@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Computer software has to be "loaded" into the [[computer storage|computer's storage]] (such as a ''[[hard drive]]'', ''memory'', or ''[[RAM]]'').@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10770570@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Once the software has loaded, the computer is able to ''execute'' the software.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10770580@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This involves passing [[instruction (computer science)|instructions]] from the application software, through the system software, to the [[hardware]] which ultimately receives the instruction as [[machine language|machine code]].@1@26@@oe@30-11-2008
10770590@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Each instruction causes the computer to carry out an operation -- moving [[data (computing)|data]], carrying out a [[computation]], or altering the [[control flow]] of instructions.@1@25@@oe@30-11-2008
10770600@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Data movement is typically from one place in memory to another.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10770610@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Sometimes it involves moving data between memory and registers which enable high-speed data access in the CPU.@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
10770620@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Moving data, especially large amounts of it, can be costly.@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10770630@unknown@formal@none@1@S@So, this is sometimes avoided by using "pointers" to data instead.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10770640@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Computations include simple operations such as incrementing the value of a variable data element.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10770650@unknown@formal@none@1@S@More complex computations may involve many operations and data elements together.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10770660@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Instructions may be performed sequentially, conditionally, or iteratively.@1@8@@oe@30-11-2008
10770670@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Sequential instructions are those operations that are performed one after another.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10770680@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Conditional instructions are performed such that different sets of instructions execute depending on the value(s) of some data.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10770690@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In some languages this is known as an "if" statement.@1@10@@oe@30-11-2008
10770700@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Iterative instructions are performed repetitively and may depend on some data value.@1@12@@oe@30-11-2008
10770710@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This is sometimes called a "loop."@1@6@@oe@30-11-2008
10770720@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Often, one instruction may "call" another set of instructions that are defined in some other program or [[module (programming)|module]].@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10770730@unknown@formal@none@1@S@When more than one computer processor is used, instructions may be executed simultaneously.@1@13@@oe@30-11-2008
10770740@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A simple example of the way software operates is what happens when a user selects an entry such as "Copy" from a menu.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10770750@unknown@formal@none@1@S@In this case, a conditional instruction is executed to copy text from data in a 'document' area residing in memory, perhaps to an intermediate storage area known as a 'clipboard' data area.@1@32@@oe@30-11-2008
10770760@unknown@formal@none@1@S@If a different menu entry such as "Paste" is chosen, the software may execute the instructions to copy the text from the clipboard data area to a specific location in the same or another document in memory.@1@37@@oe@30-11-2008
10770770@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Depending on the application, even the example above could become complicated.@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
10770780@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The field of [[software engineering]] endeavors to manage the complexity of how software operates.@1@14@@oe@30-11-2008
10770790@unknown@formal@none@1@S@This is especially true for software that operates in the context of a large or powerful [[computer system]].@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10770800@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Currently, almost the only limitations on the use of computer software in applications is the ingenuity of the designer/programmer.@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10770810@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Consequently, large areas of activities (such as playing grand master level chess) formerly assumed to be incapable of software simulation are now routinely programmed.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
10770820@unknown@formal@none@1@S@The only area that has so far proved reasonably secure from software simulation is the realm of human art— especially, pleasing music and literature.@1@24@@oe@30-11-2008
